{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658859"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20830"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97049"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11660"},{"type":"tags","id":"11661"},{"type":"tags","id":"11662"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97049"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman undergoes an ultrasound scan at 18 weeks of pregnancy. The scan reveals a foetus with an open defect in the posterior aspect of the skull and upper spine, with neural tissue exposed. The obstetrician explains that this represents a primary error of morphogenesis that occurred during early embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of congenital anomaly present in this foetus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malformation","Disruption","Deformation","Dysplasia","Sequence"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe foetus described has a neural tube defect, specifically suggesting anencephaly with spina bifida. This is a \u003Cstrong\u003Emalformation\u003C/strong\u003E, which is defined as a primary error in morphogenesis resulting from an intrinsically abnormal developmental process. In this case, the malformation results from failure of neural tube closure during primary neurulation between days 22-28 of embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption\u003C/strong\u003E - This refers to the breakdown of previously normal tissue due to extrinsic factors such as vascular accidents, infection, or mechanical forces\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeformation\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs when abnormal mechanical forces act on otherwise normal tissue, typically causing altered shape (e.g., clubfoot due to intrauterine positioning)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - This refers to abnormal organisation of cells into tissues, often affecting specific cell types (e.g., ectodermal dysplasia)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESequence\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a pattern of multiple anomalies derived from a single known or presumed structural defect or mechanical factor, rather than being a type of anomaly itself\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMalformations like neural tube defects represent intrinsically abnormal developmental processes. They may be caused by genetic factors, environmental influences, or a combination of both. Neural tube defects specifically have been linked to folate deficiency, genetic predisposition, and certain medications, highlighting their multifactorial nature.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Malformations are primary errors of morphogenesis resulting from intrinsically abnormal developmental processes.","Malformations can be caused by single gene defects, chromosomal abnormalities, or multifactorial influences.","Neural tube defects represent a classic example of malformations due to failure of neural tube closure during embryogenesis.","Developmental anomalies are classified as malformations, disruptions, deformations, or dysplasias based on their underlying mechanism."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 10; page 454."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T08:08:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T08:10:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13705"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97049"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11660"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Concepts in congenital abnormalities","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":9,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11661"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name